webpackJsonp([0xe4beff1fd4a68000],{"./node_modules/json-loader/index.js!./.cache/json/developer-ethics.json":function(e,t){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:'<h2>Developer Ethics</h2>\n<p>Developer Ethics describes the field of ethics as it is applied to the behavior of software developers.</p>\n<p>According to <a href=\'http://www.iep.utm.edu/ethics/\' target=\'_blank\' rel=\'nofollow\'>The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a>, the field of ethics (or moral philosophy) involves “systematizing, defending, and recommending concepts of right and wrong.” </p>\n<p>Over the years a number of organizations and individuals have attempted to codify developer ethics into a variety of oaths, pledges, and codes of conduct. </p>\n<p>Examples include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><a href="http://seeri.etsu.edu/TheSECode.htm"><strong>The International Standard for Professional Software Development and Ethical Responsibility</strong></a> by the IEEE-CS/ACM Joint Task Force on Software Engineering Ethics and Professional Practices</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="http://computerethicsinstitute.org/publications/tencommandments.html"><strong>The Ten Commandments of Computer Ethics</strong></a> by the Computer Ethics Institute</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="http://pledge-of-the-computing-professional.org/home-page/the-oath"><strong>The Pledge of the Computing Professional</strong></a></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="https://medium.com/@BillSourour/the-trustworthy-coders-pledge-aa5ba046c5aa"><strong>The Trustworthy Coder’s Pledge</strong></a> by Bill Sourour</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=36NgPu9OyRM&#x26;list=PLWKjhJtqVAbno-B4RmJHCDO0ZUKC2tpUQ"><strong>The Programmer’s Oath</strong></a> by “Uncle Bob” Martin</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="http://neveragain.tech"><strong>The “Never Again” Pledge</strong></a></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Common themes appearing throughout these examples include a commitment to honesty, integrity, and fairness.</p>\n<p>To date, since most software developers do not belong to – and are not governed by – any official order, guild, association, or society, no single, codified ethical standard has been widely adopted.</p>\n<p>—</p>\n<h4>More Information:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2014/entries/ethics-computer/">Computer and Information Ethics</a> entry in the Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_ethics">Computer Ethics</a> entry in WikiPedia</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="http://www3.cs.stonybrook.edu/~mueller/teaching/cse302/">CSE 302 - Professional Ethics for Computer Science</a> – outline and study materials for a course given in the Computer Science department at Stony Brook University’s College of Engineering and Applied Sciences.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20080418122849/http://www.southernct.edu/organizations/rccs/resources/research/introduction/bynum_shrt_hist.html">A Very Short History of Computer Ethics</a> – article from the Summer 2000 issue of the American Philosophical Association’s Newsletter on Philosophy and Computing</p>\n</li>\n</ul>',fields:{slug:"/developer-ethics/"},frontmatter:{title:"Developer Ethics"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/developer-ethics/"}}}});
